1.2 Feature transformation (54pt)¶

In [5]:
x1 = wdbc["area.se"]
x2 = wdbc["texture.worst"]
y = wdbc.diagnosis == "M"
X = np.column_stack((x1, x2))
m = LogisticRegression(solver="lbfgs").fit(X, y)
# Now greate the regular grid
ex1 = np.linspace(x1.min(), x1.max(), 30) # 30 elements
ex2 = np.linspace(x2.min(), x2.max(), 30)
xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
# meshgrid creates two 30x30 matrices
g = np.column_stack((xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()))
# we create the design matrix by stacking the xx1, xx2
# after unraveling those into columns
# predict on the grid
hatY = m.predict(g).reshape(30, 30)
# imshow wants a matrix, so we reshape the predicted
# vector into one
_ = plt.imshow(hatY, extent=(x1.min(), x1.max(), x2.min(), x2.max()),
aspect="auto", # let the image fit to screen
interpolation='none', origin='lower', alpha=0.3)
# you need to specify that the image begins from below,
# not above, otherwise it will be flipped around
_ = plt.scatter(x1, x2, c=y, edgecolor='k', s=8)
_ = plt.show()

(a) Use these two to model diagnosis with k-NN where k=7 using original features (i.e. not normalized features).

(b) (6pt) Plot the corresponding decision boundary (use at least 100 ×100 matrix). Explain why do you see apparently arbitrary stripes on the image (vertical stripes in case you put texture on x-axis).
In [7]:
x1 = wdbc["texture.mean"]
x2 = wdbc["concpoints.mean"]
y = wdbc.diagnosis == "M"
X = np.column_stack((x1, x2))
m = knn.fit(X, y)
# Make a function graph that takes x1, x2, y, and m and return the plot
def graph(x1, x2, y, m):
    # Now create the regular grid
    ex1 = np.linspace(x1.min(), x1.max(), 100) # 100 elements
    ex2 = np.linspace(x2.min(), x2.max(), 100)
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
    # meshgrid creates two 30x30 matrices
    g = np.column_stack((xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()))
    # we create the design matrix by stacking the xx1, xx2
    # after unraveling those into columns
    # predict on the grid
    hatY = m.predict(g).reshape(100, 100)
    # imshow wants a matrix, so we reshape the predicted vector into one
    _ = plt.imshow(hatY, extent=(x1.min(), x1.max(), x2.min(), x2.max()),
        aspect="auto", interpolation='none', origin='lower',
        # you need to specify that the image begins from below, not above, otherwise it will be flipped around
        alpha=0.3)
    _ = plt.scatter(x1, x2, c=y, edgecolor='k', s=8)
    _ = plt.show()
    
graph(x1, x2, y, m)

We see apparently arbitrary stripes on the image because the vertical axis scale is more than 10x smaller than the horizontal sclae. When plotting, this large different in scalling is reflected in the vertical stripes.

3. (10pt) Explain why does the decision boundary plot look different now. Comment on the accuracy: was accuracy better with original features or normalized features?

The decision boundary plot looks very different using the original features versus the normalized features. In the plot using normalized features, the decision boundary appears to be much neater and more accurate in terms of the plot points. This is because when we normalize texture.mean and concpoints.mean, we bring the features to the same scale. This makes it easier to understand their effects. The accuracy is significantly better with the normalized features because of this reason.

4. (10pt) now use the original (non-normalized) features and repeat the process. However, this time use Mahalanobis distance.
In [10]:
x1 = wdbc["texture.mean"]
x2 = wdbc["concpoints.mean"]
X = np.column_stack((x1, x2))
Sigma = np.cov(X, rowvar=False)
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=7, metric='mahalanobis', metric_params={'V':Sigma})
m = knn.fit(X, y)
graph(wdbc["texture.mean"], wdbc["concpoints.mean"], y, m)
scores = cross_val_score(knn, X, y, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
print('Prediction Accuracy', scores.mean())

Prediction Accuracy 0.9261278195488721

2. (24pt) Get this code to work with your image and understand what it does. Explain:
(a) What does shape of pixels mean

The shape of the pixels presents height, width, and number of color channels.

(b) What is matrix M? Why does it have 671040 rows and 3 columns in this example?

Matrix m is the result of converting the 'pixel' matrix into an Nx3 matrix, where N is the number of pixels, and 3 is the number of color channels. Each row is a pixel. That is why there are 450000 rows in the particular picture I selected since it is 600x750. In the picture provided in the problem set, there are 671040 rows because it is an image that is 699x960 which gives 671040 pixels in total. 3 indicates that there are three color channels.

(c) What do cl values tell us? E.g. if cl[12345] = 2, what does it mean?

The cl values find the cluster id for each pixel. If cl[12345] = 2, that means pixel 12345 is in cluster 2

(d) What are the columns of “center color values” printed above? E.g. the first row, second column is value 163.37. What does that number mean?

The columns of "center color values" represent the RGB values for each color. The first row, second column value 163.37 represents the Green value.

(e) How many “center color values” are there? Why do we have this number?

In the example image provided in the problem set, there are 48 center color values because there are 48 RGB values (16 colors) in the image.

3. (8pt) Next repeat the above by reducing the number of colors to 2, and 4. Show the pictures!
Hint: make a function that takes the number of colors as an argument, then you don’t have to copy-paste your code that much.
In [17]:
# Make a function that takes un the number of colors and return the image
def print_image(num_color):
    M = pixels.reshape((-1,pixels.shape[2]))
    from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
    m = KMeans(num_color).fit(M) # cluster the color values
    cl = m.predict(M) # find the cluster id for each pixel
    centers = m.cluster_centers_ # find the cluster centers (i.e. colors)
    compressed = centers[cl]/255 # normalize to between 0 and 1
    compressed = compressed.reshape(pixels.shape)
    # make it back to NxM array
    ax = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
    ax.set_aspect("equal")
    _ = plt.imshow(compressed)
    _ = plt.show()
